00:12:09,344 --> 00:12:13,185
And they all played out exactly the same way in each location.

244
00:12:13,185 --> 00:12:16,026
That way, we could have the three scenes play

245
00:12:16,026 --> 00:12:18,947
in the correct order and allow Clodian's relationship

246
00:12:18,947 --> 00:12:22,048
to progress, regardless of the order that you tackle.

247
00:12:22,508 --> 00:12:25,910
the forts.

248
00:12:25,910 --> 00:12:29,031
And it's not going to let me skip, is it?

249
00:12:29,031 --> 00:12:29,211
Okay.

250
00:12:29,211 --> 00:12:33,792
Next up, scripted sequences.

251
00:12:33,792 --> 00:12:39,534
In some ways, these are kind of interactive cut scenes in that we sometimes control the

252
00:12:39,534 --> 00:12:45,016
camera or we limit the player's moveset somehow so that we can control the moment, but the

253
00:12:45,016 --> 00:12:46,016
player is still in control.

254
00:12:46,016 --> 00:12:47,157
It's all interactive.

255
00:12:48,037 --> 00:12:49,998
Our big action set pieces fall into this category,

256
00:12:49,998 --> 00:12:53,720
though sometimes they are also used for more intimate moments,

257
00:12:53,720 --> 00:12:55,081
such as the elephant ride.

258
00:12:55,081 --> 00:12:58,283
This is our active cinematic experience.

259
00:12:58,283 --> 00:13:01,365
Like I said earlier, emotional things

260
00:13:01,365 --> 00:13:04,086
will have a lot more impact if you have it on the stick,

261
00:13:04,086 --> 00:13:04,407
in control.

262
00:13:04,407 --> 00:13:07,228
And more often than not, we use them as a climax

263
00:13:07,228 --> 00:13:07,869
to a story beat.

264
00:13:07,869 --> 00:13:10,190
Now, the thing is, we didn't actually really

265
00:13:10,190 --> 00:13:13,372
have any of these in the Western Ghats chapter,

266
00:13:13,372 --> 00:13:14,753
because in our open world scenario,

267
00:13:15,238 --> 00:13:17,599
There's no controlling the pace or the order of the approach.

268
00:13:17,599 --> 00:13:19,460
And we didn't want players to hit the high point too early.

269
00:13:19,460 --> 00:13:21,301
So we saved them for later.

270
00:13:21,301 --> 00:13:24,642
Next up, one of the key components of this chapter,

271
00:13:24,642 --> 00:13:26,923
driving dialogue.

272
00:13:26,923 --> 00:13:29,324
Given the scope of the level, we didn't

273
00:13:29,324 --> 00:13:31,945
want to force players to hoof it all over the place.

274
00:13:31,945 --> 00:13:34,326
And what better time to engage in some casual banter

275
00:13:34,326 --> 00:13:39,648
than on a cool road trip to the Western Ghats?

276
00:13:39,648 --> 00:13:42,989
So due to the degree of interactivity,

277
00:13:42,989 --> 00:13:44,650
driving dialogue has some caveats.

278
00:13:45,183 --> 00:13:48,605
First of all, there's no fixed camera, so you can't get up close and personal.

279
00:13:48,605 --> 00:13:51,866
The player could be hitting obstacles, going off drops, etc. etc.

280
00:13:51,866 --> 00:13:58,069
But the biggest thing was that these conversations can be interrupted by the player at any time,

281
00:13:58,069 --> 00:14:03,052
when they get out of the car, or entering an area of interest, or a combat zone.

282
00:14:03,052 --> 00:14:07,154
Now, we developed an interrupt system for Uncharted 4, which we carried over here,

283
00:14:07,154 --> 00:14:10,255
and that enabled us to allow the player to exit the jeep at any time

284
00:14:10,255 --> 00:14:13,197
and have the conversations resume naturally.

285
00:14:13,197 --> 00:14:14,397
But still, player.

286
00:14:14,720 --> 00:14:19,383
controlled interruptions. On top of all that, all the dialogue has to be semi-projected

287
00:14:19,383 --> 00:14:23,166
over the sound of the engine, so it's probably not the best place for Nadine to ask,

288
00:14:23,166 --> 00:14:32,033
Chloe, why do you resent your father so much? However, it was still incredibly useful for

289
00:14:32,033 --> 00:14:37,016
progressing Chlodine's relationship. Even though all the driving took place out in the open world,

290
00:14:37,016 --> 00:14:41,019
we didn't have to write the dialogue in a neutral tone because we could progress the

291
00:14:41,019 --> 00:14:42,460
connection between the characters.

292
00:14:43,222 --> 00:14:45,643
we could break up the conversations into phases,

293
00:14:45,643 --> 00:14:47,003
just like we did for the cut scenes.

294
00:14:47,003 --> 00:14:49,885
The first conversation would play at the start of the level,

295
00:14:49,885 --> 00:14:51,526
the second conversation would play

296
00:14:51,526 --> 00:14:52,986
after you got back into the Jeep

297
00:14:52,986 --> 00:14:55,327
when finishing the first fort, and so on and so on.

298
00:14:55,327 --> 00:14:58,549
So we were able to utilize topics and moments

299
00:14:58,549 --> 00:15:00,410
that would have made the cut scenes drag,

300
00:15:00,410 --> 00:15:02,431
but sound perfectly natural while driving around.

301
00:15:02,431 --> 00:15:05,332
Now, before writing these conversations,

302
00:15:05,332 --> 00:15:06,813
we did have to determine how long

303
00:15:06,813 --> 00:15:08,114
the player would be in the Jeep,

304
00:15:08,114 --> 00:15:10,375
and then write the conversations to fit in that time.

305
00:15:11,200 --> 00:15:13,121
And since they knew the level better than anyone,

306
00:15:13,121 --> 00:15:15,383
I asked our QA team to find the shortest time

307
00:15:15,383 --> 00:15:17,144
between key landmarks.

308
00:15:17,144 --> 00:15:19,665
And it turns out the answer was 15 to 20 seconds.

309
00:15:19,665 --> 00:15:22,007
Now, obviously most players will take longer,

310
00:15:22,007 --> 00:15:23,908
but it served as a good guide for how many seconds

311
00:15:23,908 --> 00:15:24,968
the players would definitely hear.

312
00:15:24,968 --> 00:15:27,910
Because once the player entered the next fort,

313
00:15:27,910 --> 00:15:30,051
the current conversation would not be resumed later.

314
00:15:30,051 --> 00:15:32,333
One, because it would be too long a separation.

315
00:15:32,333 --> 00:15:34,414
It could be as long as like 20 minutes.

316
00:15:34,414 --> 00:15:36,395
And two, all the conversations would just end up

317
00:15:36,395 --> 00:15:37,155
bunching up at the end.

318
00:15:38,572 --> 00:15:41,732
So when writing, I broke the long conversations into three chunks,

319
00:15:41,732 --> 00:15:43,273
each about 15 to 20 seconds long.

320
00:15:43,273 --> 00:15:47,174
So the first chunk was a bit vital to Clodine's character arcs.

321
00:15:47,174 --> 00:15:49,335
You know, here we have Nadine assessing her current status

322
00:15:49,335 --> 00:15:52,335
and Chloe throwing in a bit of her personal philosophy.

323
00:15:52,335 --> 00:15:54,836
And you would definitely hear this bit before getting to the next fort.

324
00:15:54,836 --> 00:15:57,317
The second chunk built on the first

325
00:15:57,317 --> 00:15:59,797
with a bit of Chloe backstory and some Nadine philosophy.

326
00:15:59,797 --> 00:16:01,838
You would probably hear this,

327
00:16:01,838 --> 00:16:03,358
but if you didn't, it wasn't the end of the world.

328
00:16:03,358 --> 00:16:06,499
And then the last chunk, after a pause from the previous ones,

329
00:16:06,499 --> 00:16:08,000
would usually reserve for banter.

330
00:16:08,390 --> 00:16:11,410
A chance to see the characters talk about things in the outside world.

331
00:16:11,410 --> 00:16:14,091
Fun, but not essential, and if you missed it, no big deal.

332
00:16:14,091 --> 00:16:16,952
Now, while this was tricky to plan out,

333
00:16:16,952 --> 00:16:21,313
it was still relatively easy to control the tone and progression of Clodine's relationship,

334
00:16:21,313 --> 00:16:25,554
because we knew when the player would be hearing each conversation.

335
00:16:25,554 --> 00:16:28,915
However, this was not the case for level dialogue.

336
00:16:28,915 --> 00:16:33,156
Now, this is the stuff that's spoken by the characters while exploring the level.

337
00:16:33,156 --> 00:16:33,736
100% interactive.

338
00:16:33,736 --> 00:16:38,077
So, to account for all the branching and for all the character progression possibilities...

339
00:16:38,333 --> 00:16:41,074
we wrote and recorded nearly three times as much dialogue

340
00:16:41,074 --> 00:16:42,834
for this level than we did for the largest

341
00:16:42,834 --> 00:16:44,515
level in Uncharted 4.

342
00:16:44,515 --> 00:16:45,135
Yow.

343
00:16:45,135 --> 00:16:49,856
On a base level, level dialogue is useful for several things,

344
00:16:49,856 --> 00:16:52,257
giving little nudges and hints, supplementing

345
00:16:52,257 --> 00:16:54,257
environmental storytelling, and filling

346
00:16:54,257 --> 00:16:56,878
in the historical backstory that would have bloated

347
00:16:56,878 --> 00:16:58,298
the length of the cut scenes.

348
00:16:58,298 --> 00:16:59,778
So here's an example from that.

349
00:16:59,778 --> 00:17:01,999
Hey, look, our moments.

350
00:17:01,999 --> 00:17:02,739
You were right, Nadine.

351
00:17:02,739 --> 00:17:04,259
I have my moments.

352
00:17:04,259 --> 00:17:06,100
You thought versions?

353
00:17:07,578 --> 00:17:10,401
It looks to be a mix of Persian and Hoisina.

354
00:17:10,401 --> 00:17:11,281
Here's one of the things.

355
00:17:11,281 --> 00:17:15,305
So, nice and simple, but sort of helps build things along.

356
00:17:15,305 --> 00:17:21,170
But, level dialogue is equally important for creating a large number of little tiny character moments.

357
00:17:21,170 --> 00:17:23,132
These little moments can really add up to a lot.

358
00:17:23,132 --> 00:17:25,514
And this is where you can get the subtlety in.

359
00:17:25,514 --> 00:17:28,997
Not that the dialogue has to be subtle, and frankly it often isn't,

360
00:17:28,997 --> 00:17:32,901
but over time you build that slow, gradual relationship.

361
00:17:33,413 --> 00:17:38,837
And like I said earlier, when you can get these moments in the gameplay on the stick,

362
00:17:38,837 --> 00:17:42,639
they have a lot more impact on the player.

363
00:17:42,639 --> 00:17:47,442
So here's an example of what we can do through a classic Uncharted valving mechanic.

364
00:17:47,442 --> 00:17:48,643
Pull-ups.

365
00:17:48,643 --> 00:17:50,965
Here, give me your hand.

366
00:17:50,965 --> 00:17:55,968
No matter what the player does, Chloe will not take Nadine's hand in this clip.

367
00:17:55,968 --> 00:17:56,788
I'm good, actually.

368
00:17:56,788 --> 00:17:57,148
Okay.

369
00:17:57,148 --> 00:17:58,669
Here, I've got you.

370
00:17:58,669 --> 00:17:59,650
Alright, I can manage.

371
00:17:59,650 --> 00:18:00,771
Just accept my help.

372
00:18:00,771 --> 00:18:02,932
Here, though, she doesn't have a choice.

373
00:18:04,067 --> 00:18:05,208
Come on up.

374
00:18:05,208 --> 00:18:07,511
Only because you said please.

375
00:18:07,511 --> 00:18:08,211
I didn't expect you.

376
00:18:08,211 --> 00:18:08,512
Oh, no, not me.

377
00:18:08,512 --> 00:18:19,002
OK, so that last clip was cheating a little bit

378
00:18:19,002 --> 00:18:21,865
because it was part of a small mini cutscene.

379
00:18:21,865 --> 00:18:25,868
However, I wanted to point out that up until this point in the game,

380
00:18:25,868 --> 00:18:27,090
that point in the game,

381
00:18:27,402 --> 00:18:30,223
Nadine calls Chloe by her last name, Frazier.

382
00:18:30,223 --> 00:18:32,244
This is the first time that she ever calls her Chloe.

383
00:18:32,244 --> 00:18:35,326
And this is something else that we build up to over the course of the game,

384
00:18:35,326 --> 00:18:39,147
using that same mechanic that's very familiar.

385
00:18:39,147 --> 00:18:43,169
Now, we also use level dialogue to give characters more character.

386
00:18:43,169 --> 00:18:47,312
It took us a while to calibrate Nadine's personality.

387
00:18:47,312 --> 00:18:49,433
At first, we made her way too harsh in our early drafts.

388
00:18:49,433 --> 00:18:54,715
And I really wanted to give her something that you wouldn't necessarily expect from a hardened mercenary.

389
00:18:55,595 --> 00:18:57,776
And one night I was thinking of these old animal fact cards

390
00:18:57,776 --> 00:19:00,277
that they used to advertise on TV when I was a kid.

391
00:19:00,277 --> 00:19:02,519
And yeah, $1, $1.

392
00:19:02,519 --> 00:19:07,982
And I thought, what if Nadine grew up with a set of these?

393
00:19:07,982 --> 00:19:09,543
And the answer is this.

394
00:19:09,543 --> 00:19:10,163
What?

395
00:19:10,163 --> 00:19:13,145
They're just large flying rodents.

396
00:19:13,145 --> 00:19:14,106
Actually, no, they're not.

397
00:19:14,106 --> 00:19:14,826
Yeah, they are.

398
00:19:14,826 --> 00:19:17,748
They're closer to primates than needles.

399
00:19:17,748 --> 00:19:19,889
OK, well, I'll look it up.

400
00:19:19,889 --> 00:19:21,190
Fraser, over here.

401
00:19:21,190 --> 00:19:21,470
Look.

402
00:19:21,470 --> 00:19:21,770
What?

403
00:19:21,770 --> 00:19:22,671
What is it?

404
00:19:22,671 --> 00:19:23,591
Monkeys.

405
00:19:23,591 --> 00:19:25,072
You seem excited.

406
00:19:25,979 --> 00:19:27,180
I like monkeys.

407
00:19:27,180 --> 00:19:29,983
That's Vesuki, a king of the Nagas,

408
00:19:29,983 --> 00:19:34,006
entities that take the form of the King Cobra.

409
00:19:34,006 --> 00:19:37,850
It shows his control over fear and death.

410
00:19:37,850 --> 00:19:41,633
Cobras were always my favorite snake.

411
00:19:41,633 --> 00:19:42,574
Don't think I have a favorite snake.

412
00:19:42,574 --> 00:19:45,076
So there are many more examples, but this is kind of a way

413
00:19:45,076 --> 00:19:48,439
to sneak in some little quirks into Nadine's character

414
00:19:48,439 --> 00:19:50,601
without necessarily cluttering up the cut scenes with it.

415
00:19:51,967 --> 00:19:54,448
Now, another tool sort of related to level dialogue

416
00:19:54,448 --> 00:19:56,009
in our arsenal, if there's something

417
00:19:56,009 --> 00:19:58,611
that we want to convey and the gameplay space is just

418
00:19:58,611 --> 00:20:00,672
a little too tight to fit it, we will sometimes

419
00:20:00,672 --> 00:20:03,293
drop in a optional dialogue prompt.

420
00:20:03,293 --> 00:20:07,176
Now, if the player chooses to engage, the dialogue plays out

421
00:20:07,176 --> 00:20:09,077
and we put the player into a forced walk

422
00:20:09,077 --> 00:20:11,298
and they can't climb or otherwise interact.

423
00:20:11,298 --> 00:20:13,600
It's not ideal, but sometimes it's necessary.

424
00:20:14,208 --> 00:20:18,309
Now, you can't guarantee that the player is going to hear the dialogue,

425
00:20:18,309 --> 00:20:25,352
but most people have this Pavlovian reaction to seeing a button propped.

426
00:20:25,352 --> 00:20:29,573
So, sometimes we put in a little exposition,

427
00:20:29,573 --> 00:20:33,034
sometimes a little character moment, and sometimes a little bit of both.

428
00:20:33,034 --> 00:20:33,254
Wow, nice shot.

429
00:20:33,254 --> 00:20:36,736
Persians must have had a trebuchet.

430
00:20:36,736 --> 00:20:37,356
A trebuchet?

431
00:20:37,356 --> 00:20:40,857
Can't you just say catapult like a normal person?

432
00:20:41,504 --> 00:20:43,205
A trebuchet is a type of catapult.

433
00:20:43,205 --> 00:20:47,127
It can handle heavier projectiles, like this one.

434
00:20:47,127 --> 00:20:49,448
And fling them longer distances.

435
00:20:49,448 --> 00:20:54,750
Right. You learned that in your military training?

436
00:20:54,750 --> 00:20:57,451
I looked it up on Wikipedia.

437
00:20:57,451 --> 00:21:00,012
Like a normal person.

438
00:21:00,012 --> 00:21:00,593
Hey! Where's Sam?

439
00:21:00,593 --> 00:21:01,133
Don't think he has a rope?

440
00:21:01,133 --> 00:21:01,653
Oh, right. Forgot about that.

441
00:21:01,653 --> 00:21:02,213
He can sort it out.

442
00:21:02,213 --> 00:21:05,835
Hey, thanks for not murdering Sam, by the way.

443
00:21:05,835 --> 00:21:08,156
We might prove useful later.

444
00:21:08,156 --> 00:21:10,757
There you go. Good. Positive attitude.

445
00:21:11,758 --> 00:21:13,378
Good act as a key point.

446
00:21:13,378 --> 00:21:16,519
Brought some fire away from us.

447
00:21:16,519 --> 00:21:21,920
Blown himself on a grenade and saved us all.

448
00:21:21,920 --> 00:21:22,080
Come on.

449
00:21:22,080 --> 00:21:23,920
We're exposed up here.

450
00:21:23,920 --> 00:21:27,101
You know, I feel so much safer with her around.

451
00:21:27,101 --> 00:21:30,401
I never would have found you without her help, OK?

452
00:21:30,401 --> 00:21:30,842
OK.

453
00:21:30,842 --> 00:21:32,542
She just wants to kill me.

454
00:21:32,542 --> 00:21:34,422
Well, don't give her a reason to.

455
00:21:34,422 --> 00:21:37,643
So all that stuff, all those different techniques

456
00:21:37,643 --> 00:21:40,443
for level dialogue worth.

457
00:21:40,902 --> 00:21:45,544
beautifully in, I need a little more time because we started late.

458
00:21:45,544 --> 00:21:48,046
All this stuff works beautifully in linear design.

459
00:21:48,046 --> 00:21:51,607
And the way that we designed our cut scenes and our driving dialogue, we still had control

460
00:21:51,607 --> 00:21:51,907
over those.

461
00:21:51,907 --> 00:21:56,369
But the dialogue and the ports themselves, or anywhere else in the world, no.

462
00:21:56,369 --> 00:22:01,812
Since the player could explore the port interiors and other places in any order, what we wrote

463
00:22:01,812 --> 00:22:03,373
couldn't have a linear progression.

464
00:22:03,373 --> 00:22:06,094
It could wreck the flow if you hit it at the wrong time.

465
00:22:06,094 --> 00:22:08,655
So again, we wrote the dialogue with a neutral tone to reflect that.

466
00:22:09,217 --> 00:22:13,718
But we could build on the neutral dialogue to better reflect the current state of Clodine's relationship.

467
00:22:13,718 --> 00:22:16,999
Depending on where you were and how many forts you completed,

468
00:22:16,999 --> 00:22:20,520
we could add to or replace the neutral dialogue with something more friendly.

469
00:22:20,520 --> 00:22:23,341
There are literally hundreds of places we did this in the level.

470
00:22:23,341 --> 00:22:26,062
So here's an example of how we build on neutral dialogue.

471
00:22:26,062 --> 00:22:29,863
The neutral version, the one that plays if this is the first fort you've found, come first.

472
00:22:29,863 --> 00:22:32,804
Then we build on it a little for the second, and then more for the third.

